    <string name="offloading_guide">This runs music on a dedicated audio chip instead of the main CPU, which can reduce battery usage and heat. Some devices or audio formats may not support offloading, which can lead to playback issues or missing features. If you want better battery life, enabling offloading can help, but if problems occur it may be due to the audio format, device limitations, or specific offloading options needing to be toggled.</string>
    <string name="position_fixing">Position fixing</string>
    <string name="position_fixing_guide">Position fix helps keep the playback timeline in sync when offloading is enabled. On certain phone models, this can cause timing issues that result in distortion, pauses, or audio failing to play. If you experience these problems while offloading, disabling position fixing may resolve them.</string>
    <string name="silence_skipped_guide">When enabled, silent sections of audio are skipped automatically. This can interfere with seeking behavior, such as returning to a previous track or position. For this reason, silence skipping is disabled by default.</string>
    <string name="playback_speed_guide">This controls how fast or slow audio plays and may affect how voices sound. A value of 1.0 is normal speed, values below slow playback down, and values above speed it up, with a minimum of 0.1 and a maximum of 2.0.</string>
    <string name="load_control_guide">This controls how much audio is buffered during playback and affects responsiveness, seek behavior, and playback stability. Default aims to work well in most cases, Low Latency prioritizes fast starts and quick seeks but can be unstable, Balanced offers a mix of responsiveness and reliability, and High Stability focuses on smooth, uninterrupted playback at the cost of slower startup.</string>
